<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Whiplash evidence</title></head><body><div><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:left;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">5</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:14pt">Written evidence from Robert Hay (CMI 001)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Evidence of Robert Hay FRCSE Orthopaedic Surgeon to the select committee on “Reducing the cost of Whiplash Claims”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">My Qualifications</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Qualified MB ChB Edinburgh </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Trained and qualified in general and then Orthopaedic Surgery</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">L</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ecturer in orthopaedic Surgery </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">University of Edinburgh</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Lecturer in orthopaedic and spinal Surgery   University of Hong Kong</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Spinal and orthopaedic surgeon Duchess of Kent Childrens Orthopaedic Hospital</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Orthopaedic and trauma Surgeon SE Thames Regional health Authority 25 Yrs</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Retained expert in innumerable personal injury cases</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ummary </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">It is my belief that an undesirable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> provider driven</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> whiplash industry has developed in this country that defrauds the insurance industry and that the vast majority of such claims are exaggerated or contrived</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, and that the current adversarial legal system is an inappropriate tool for assessing damages</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I have had extensive experience in the management and treatment of spinal, including neck injury, both within and outwith</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the medico legal context. I have written many hundreds of medical reports for both claimant and defendant in personal injury litigation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I am well informed on the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">large body of medical evidence on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the subject, and in passing would recommend any party interested in this subject to Malleson’s scholarly book “Whiplash and other useful Illnesses.” McGill Press.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The clinical problem</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Although a high speed rear end impact can cause severe, and occasionally fatal injury the vast majority of  whiplash claims are the result of lesser and frequently trivial impacts.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">On impact the occupant’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">head is first jerked backwards </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and rebounds off the head restraint. Extreme hyperextension of the neck which prompted the first use (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">USA</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 1938) of the term “</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">whiplash” does not now occur because of universal head restraints. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It is very rare in whiplash cases for there to be any truly objective signs of injury. X rays are usually taken defensively if the patient attends hospital and rarely show any abnormality </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I shall use the term </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">PUWC (Prolonged Unconfirmable Whiplash Complaints)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the following discussion into which category the vast majority of whiplash claimants fall.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The injury is best regarded as a sprain of the neck which is expected to give rise to some pain and stiffness for a few weeks like sprains elsewhere in the body (eg sprained ankle) and then return to normal.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The usual claimant however continues with complaints months or years after recovery is expected,  Such persistence of symptoms are often ratified and encouraged by persons whose income depends on offering treatment eg physiotherapists, osteopaths, and the transcription of symptoms into documents and case notes often gives a spurious ratification to symptoms.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In the assessment of injury therefore no reliance should be placed on the observations of anyone with a pecuniary interest in the case.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Early access to physiotherapy (the rehabilitation code) has compounded the problem appearing to ratify injury before the presence or absence of injury has been assessed. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Claim</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Problem</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In recent years following similar process in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">USA</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the number of whiplash cases seeking compensation has risen alarmingly for the following reasons. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Responsibility for the impact is held to dwell with the striking vehicle making no issue on liability</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Insurance companies often prefer to settle rather than expose themselves to the risks of defending the case in court, thus encouraging others.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A whiplash industry has developed parasitic upon the insurance companies with many persons (doctors, lawyers, physiotherapists accident management firms etc) dependant directly or indirectly on such claims for their income and therefore with a vested interest in its continuance</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The very term “whiplash” is emotive and polarising. If it had been called “learner drivers neck” and had the offence of “stopping suddenly without adequate warning” been introduced, thus transferring the blame to the vehicle in front there would be no PUWC problem. The incidence of blameworthy diseases can be profoundly influenced by changing their names (repetitive strain injury decreased dramatically when it was changed to “reversible fatigue syndrome”). Responsibility suppresses symptoms, outrage inflates symptoms.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Patients often spend the money which their advisors have led them to expect in compensation, making the winning of damages a necessity.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The proper impartial expert is an experienced orthopaedic or accident surgeon. This will usually not produce the sympathetic and colourful report required by the accident management firms who increasingly resort to poorly qualified and inadequately experienced experts who have never worked in the field of spinal injury. One overseas General practitioner with a minor degree in gynaecology was until recently writing fourteen or fifteen reports a day on neck injury an area in which he had no clinical experience.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Diagnosis</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Genuine significant neck injury</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for example fracture or dislocation or both</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> presents </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">no</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> difficulty in diagnosis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Without such damage the injury is a ligament or muscle strain and spontaneous recovery is expected within a matter of weeks.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Finding a investigation (scan</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">x ray or blood test) to confirm whiplash in the hope of distinguishing the genuine from the fraudulent is a forlorn hope, certainly with current technology.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The fraudulent is easily identified by the perceptive expert, but persons with a pecuniary interest in management or an expert with ambitions to expand their practice will not do so.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Among the features which I have found consistent in the fraudulent claimant are</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.92pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The pain is like toothache</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.92pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I can’t do the hoovering</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.92pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I can’t play with my grandchildren/children</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.92pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I’m on heavy painkillers (which give no relief)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.92pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Sunglasses worn indoors</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.92pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Asking a relative to help them undress for examination</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.92pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Walking stick used inappropriately</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Remarkable facts on PUWC =  (Protracted Unconfirmable Whiplash Complaints), which give grounds for suspicion of overstatement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.92pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is a disorder of the needy. I have never seen in forty years of practice in spinal injury seen prolonged unconfirmable symptoms in a busy, productive or wealthy person. Money is the driver.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.92pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The incidence of whiplash claims have risen rapidly at the same time as the almost universal introduction of the means of preventing such injuries (head restraints)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.92pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">PUWC injuries are not seen in drivers or passengers in the vehicle responsible for the accident. (head jerked forwards) although injury is often claimed in vehicles which come to a sudden standstill as a result of striking the side of a vehicle which pulled negligently in front of them.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.92pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">PUWC are not seen in injuries sustained in sport, or on fairground rides or dodgems or Destruction Derbys where any neck strain can be construed as self inflicted. Blame is an essential ingredient. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.92pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Patients often consult a car hire firm, a lawyer, or accident management firm before seeking medical advice.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.92pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is often a significant time lapse some times of several weeks before the patient seeks medical advice and entries in the General Practitioner’s notes like “feels OK but wants it logged” Or “doesn’t want to go back to work yet, Claim continuing”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are commonplace.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:104%; margin:0pt 12.45pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">After settlement the claimant often makes a s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">urprising recovery which they </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">attribute, not to the pay out, but to some unconventional </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">treatment </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">which was </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">not</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.55pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">available</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.45pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">them</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.75pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">while</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.6pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">litigation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:1.3pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">proceeded</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:-0.4pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">("The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">doctors</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:1.05pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">did</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:1.05pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nothing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.7pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">but two</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:1.45pt"> </span><span style="font-f